post_text:
Learning Numbers
Ms. Rena and Mrs. McDonald's class have been learning numbers. The students have been working on number chants, identifying numbers, writing numbers in order, and counting out objects when told a number. Some have even learned how to write in missing numbers of a sequence.

post_text:
Math Meets Literacy!
In Mr. Copeland and Mrs. R. Pope's 2nd grade class, students have the opportunity to expand their mastery of second grade math standards through the integration of literacy. Students were amazed to read about ways that math applies to their everyday lives. After reading, students have opportunities to take part in choosing which activities they would like to do from the Enrichment board, located in the classroom resource center.

post_text:
Message from Mr. Ethredge,

A review of progress reports at every grade level reveals that we have many students who are not meeting expectations, especially in regards to completed/submitted work. While I realize there were many challenges regarding computer and internet issues, our expectation is that each student will complete their assignments. Teachers have worked with parents and family members to try to resolve many of these issues. Progress Reports go home Wednesday, 9/9/20 and should be signed and returned by Thursday, 9/10/20. Averages at progress report time can change based on student performance over the next 4 1/2 weeks. However, grades earned at the completion of each 9 weeks grading period are final. Please help us by ensuring your child is completing all assignments in a timely manner and please report any specific issues as soon as they arise.

Thank you,
Pat Ethredge

post_text:
Message from Mrs. Couey:

Good evening Bulldog Family,
Because we have already had two weeks of virtual learning, we have changed the September 16th digital learning day to a regular school day. Students will need to come to school that day.

We are happy to announce that our Wheeler County Schools phone app is now ready. You can visit the Google Play Store or the Apple Store and search for Wheeler County Schools to download the app. We will be able to push out notifications to your phone and the app is tied to our website where you will be able to find more detailed information. Please download the app today to ensure you receive important information from the district and schools.

Our high school softball team will hold senior night next Tuesday, September 8th, at 5:00 PM. Come help us support our senior players and help cheer our softball team to victory.

Progress reports will go out next Wednesday. They will need to be signed and returned on Thursday.

Enjoy our long weekend in observance of Labor Day. Students and staff will return on Tuesday, September 8th.

For shorter wait times at our drive thru COVID 19 site at Wheeler County Health Department, please pre-register. You can pre-register one of two ways:
1. Click here https://covid19.dph.ga.gov. An email address is required. You will receive a QR code via email that you will need to bring to the site.
2. Call 478-275-6570 Monday-Friday 8-5 and Saturday 9-2. They can help you register over the phone.

If you do not pre-register, you can still be tested. You may just have a longer wait time.

post_text: During the week of August 24-28, 2020, we would like for our students to apply Habit 3: Put First Things First into their daily lives. When you "put first things first", you work then play. One way you can apply this habit is to make a schedule of priorities and then follow it. Reward yourself when you have done all of things on your to do list. We know that our students will become more disciplined and organized if they follow this habit.

Parents:
When you sign in with your parent code and create your parent account on Schoology, you are able to see all of your child's work. However, your student MUST sign in with his/her username and login to complete their work. A child CANNOT complete his/her work from the parent's account view. We apologize for the confusion. Please make sure your student is logging into Schoology using his/her username and password that was given to them by their teacher.

post_text: The week of August 17-21, our WCES Leader in Me habit is, Habit 2: Begin with the end in Mind. Begin with the end in mind means to begin each day, task, or project with a clear vision of your desired direction and destination. Someone who thinks with the end in mind says, ‚ÄúI plan ahead and set goals.‚Äù One of the best ways to incorporate Habit 2 into your life is to develop a goal(s) sheet. Write down your goals for the day and mark them off as they are completed. We would love for you to share how your child is using Habit 2: Begin with the end in mind while at home during our virtual learning.

WCES OPEN HOUSE (THURSDAY, AUGUST 6, 2020)
5TH GRADE STUDENTS ONLY!

5th Grade 8:30-10:30

WCES is asking all visitors to follow the guidelines below when attending Open House:

*You will not be able to go to any other grade level regardless, only 5th GRADE!

*Please wear an appropriate mask or face covering when in the building/classroom.

*Please try to maintain appropriate social distancing whenever possible (6 feet‚Ä¶family groups can/should stay together).

*While we welcome everyone, we ask that families limit the number of visitors to include only parents and students when possible. Children must stay with their parents and will not be allowed to roam throughout the building.

Important: Open House is not mandatory, but this will be the parents‚Äô only chance to visit their child‚Äôs classroom before school starts on Friday. Visitors will not be allowed to go to the classrooms on the first day of school.

WCES OPEN HOUSE STARTS TOMORROW!!

Pre-K and Kindergarten ONLY (1:00 -3:00)

WCES is asking all visitors to follow the guidelines below when attending Open House:

*You will not be able to go to any other grade level regardless, only Pre-k and Kindergarten on Monday, August 3, 2020.

*Please wear an appropriate mask or face covering when in the building/classroom.

*Please try to maintain appropriate social distancing whenever possible (6 feet‚Ä¶family groups can/should stay together).

*While we welcome everyone, we ask that families limit the number of visitors to include only parents and students when possible. Children must stay with their parents and will not be allowed to roam throughout the building.

Important: Open House is not mandatory, but this will be the parents‚Äô only chance to visit their child‚Äôs classroom before school starts on Friday. Visitors will not be allowed to go to the classrooms on the first day of school.

post_text:
WCES Open House

*****Parents, if you have not heard from your child‚Äôs teacher by this Friday, PLEASE call the school to set up a time to visit.

***Visitors will not be allowed to go to the classrooms on the first day of school.***

WCES will offer a face-to-face Open House for parents and students for the 2020-2021 school year. Open House will be held by grade level on different days, and due to concerns regarding Covid-19, teachers will contact families to schedule a time to visit. Each grade level will have a two-hour block of time divided into thirty minute segments. Teachers should schedule approximately five families to visit during the thirty minute segments.

8/3/20 (Monday) ‚Äì Pre-K and Kindergarten 1:00-3:00
8/4/20 (Tuesday) ‚Äì 1st Grade 8:30-10:30 and 2nd Grade 1:00-3:00
8/5/20 (Wednesday) ‚Äì 3rd Grade 8:30-10:30 and 4th Grade 1:00-3:00
8/6/20 (Thursday) ‚Äì 5th Grade 8:30-10:30

Important: Open House is not mandatory, but this will be the parents‚Äô only chance to visit their child‚Äôs classroom before school starts.

Wheeler County School System is accepting applications for a school nurse (LPN or RN) for Wheeler County Middle High School (to serve grades 6-12). Applications can be submitted by any of the following methods:
Email completed application to

suzanne.couey@wheeler.k12.ga.us

Fax completed application to (912) 568-7198

Submit in person at WCSS Board Office (18 McRae Street; Alamo, GA).

Georgia Department of Education
July 2 at 6:47 AM ¬∑

For the third year, the Georgia Foundation for Public Education, the foundation of the Georgia Department of Education, is providing Rural Education Fund grants to help rural schools and districts meet their students' needs.

A limited number of grants of up to $5,000 each are available, and any public school or school district located in a Georgia county with a population of 35,000 or less is eligible to apply. All applicants must propose a project that would solve a current challenge within the school or district and would lead to positive student outcomes.

Click here for more information: https://www.gadoe.org/External-Affairs-and-Policy/communications/Pages/PressReleaseDetails.aspx?PressView=default&pid=785

post_text:
From our Wheeler County School Nutrition:
We will make our final bus delivery of meals TODAY! (Memorial Day).

Beginning Thursday, the 28th, we will have pickup at the middle/high school only from 11-2. Pickup will be at the cafeteria dock located behind the school. Please enter through the bus shop gate, come up to dock to pick up and exit out the automated gate. WE ENCOURAGE YOU TO BRING A COOLER FOR MILK/COLD FOODS. Families will receive 6 days of breakfast and lunch per child.

IF you KNOW you will not be home on Monday, please notify one of our school personnel so we can adjust our numbers. We are thankful to have had the opportunity to continue to serve our students and families during this time.

Need PowerSchool Access?
WE ARE HERE TO HELP!

Due to school closure as a result of the Coronavirus (COVID-19) Report cards will ONLY be available online via PowerSchool‚Äôs Parent Access Portal.

To access the online Report Card, parents/guardian must have a Parent Access Portal Account. At this time paper-based report cards will not be printed.

**Wheeler County Pre-K AND Kindergarten registration**

Wheeler County Pre-K and Kindergarten registration will be THIS WEEK, May 11-14, 2020 8:00-1:00 for the 2020-2021 school year. Parents/ Guardians that requested an application to be mailed to you earlier in April can come by and drop it off this week at school.

Vital documents are still required as part of the registration .
Pre-K student:
If you are registering for Pre-k you will need social security card, birth certificate and proof of residency (light bill, water bill, rent/lease agreement or receipt, tax bill from land/house taxes).

Kindergarten student-
If you are registering for Kindergarten, you will need social security card, birth certificate, Form 3300: Certificate of Vision, Hearing, Dental and. Nutrition Screening, Form 3231 Certificate of Immunization and proof of residency (light bill, water bill, rent/lease agreement or receipt, tax bill from land/house taxes).

If you have any questions about registration, please contact Mrs. Jenny Pickle @ 912-568-7159 WCES or through our school messenger. Thank you!

Frequently Asked Questions for Students and Parents

Please refer to the linked document for answers to frequently asked questions:
Frequently Asked Questions for Students and Parents

Two of the questions and answers are included below for quick reference:

Where can I submit a question?
From your computer, visit our website (www.wheelercountyschools.org ). In the middle of the far right of the page, you will see a tab that says ‚ÄúContact Us.‚Äù Click on it and complete the form OR click on ‚Äú2020 Information,‚Äù the top right tab on our home page, scroll down to ‚ÄúContact‚Äù and submit your question there.

Where is the best place to find information about Wheeler County Schools?
Information will be updated on our webpage under News and Announcements (middle of page) and under 2020 Information (top right tab) in the following sections: For Students, For Parents, and COVID-19 Information. We will also provide call outs for important information.

Self-service options include:

Apply for Food Stamp and Medicaid Benefits
Visit: gateway.ga.gov (verification documents can also be uploaded and case status info is available for all benefits)

Download an Application:
https://dfcs.georgia.gov/services

Electronic Benefits Transfer (EBT)

Visit: https://www.connectebt.com/gaebtclient or call: 888-421-3281 for updates

Those without internet access can contact the DFCS Customer Contact Center at 877-423-4746 for additional information or to request a paper application. Once completed, applications and any required verification can be mailed back to your local county DFCS office. County office locations are available online at https://dfcs.georgia.gov/locations.

post_text:
Corona Virus
Corona means ‚Äúcrown‚Äù. The crown attaches to other cells in your lungs and infects the cell.
The Corona Virus has an oily surface. When we use soap to wash our hands the soap destroys the oil so the virus washes away.
Our class conducted an experiment to see the effects of soap on the oily surface of the virus. We used milk and food coloring to represent the virus. We poured the milk into the plate and dropped food coloring on the milk. We then dropped soap into the milk and watched the soap break-up the fat in the milk. Soap breaks-up the oils on the virus‚Äô surface so the virus can be washed away.
Germs are Everywhere!
Please Wash Your Hands!

post_text: Wheeler County Elementary School celebrated Arbor Day with a visit from Wheeler County Forestry. Learning about Georgia‚Äôs land and the variety of forest types and how the diverse ecosystems found in our state are a big component of our rich land. The students learned a lot about trees, roots, proper planting, and the importance of trees. The forest rangers took great effort in teaching and inspiring students to plant and cultivate trees. Much of the information and hands-on learning correlated well with the teaching standards. Our teachers and students enjoyed learning with the planting activity, and the teachers even had fun playing a tree trivia game.

post_text:
Mrs. Van Houten's Fifth Grade Math Classes
The main focus in Mrs. Van Houten's fifth grade math classes have been mastering multiplication, division, and exploring everything about fractions. The students have learned how to add and subtract fractions with unlike denominators, multiply a fraction by a whole number (scaling), simplify improper and proper fractions, find equivalent fractions, and turn fractions into decimals. WCES fifth graders have worked extremely hard this year and will be learning about coordinate planes in the weeks to come. As the students approach Georgia Milestones, the teachers ask parents, friends, and community for prayers and support as the 3rd, 4th, and 5th graders prepare for this end of the year test and show what ALL they have learned throughout the 2019-2020 school year. These students have had a lot of fun while working hard and Mrs. Van Houten is so proud of all of them.
